title: EU Parliament President Warns of New Libyan Migration Crisis
content:
A very thought-provoking point. I have some comments elsewhere on this thread on what might happen in the coming weeks. At any rate, here's my take on Saif:
Haftar's LNA is likely to soon gain control of the Libyan coast between Tripoli and the Tunisian border, an area where many of the migrant boats have been launched. And he may then get control of the area between Tripoli and Misrata, the other coastline with launchpoints. The strategy here is to isolate those two centers rather than get tied down in urban warfare. That will give Haftar control of at least 99% of Libyan territory. And he, and no one else, will be the new strongman there.
So what about Saif? We should be concerned for what mischief he could cause, but it may be he will try to leave the country, if some other place is willing to take him. There are still Gaddafi family members and regime supporters in exile, and they seem to have more than enough money to live on. They might be able to make some mischief from exile. But will they? Any efforts seem doomed from the start.
But if Saif stays in Libya, he will likely not do well opposing Haftar. Haftar has Egyptian support, and may now be getting Gulf Arab money, or certainly more than he has been getting. Most Libyans might miss Gaddafi, but they want a restoration of public safety and security, and getting the benefits of the oil industry coming their way again. The question is, would most Libyans be willing to make a break with the past (Gaddafi and his family) to ensure a strong government that would get the economy back in shape? If so, I'd certainly bet on Haftar, and not Saif.
Under the circumstances, what Saif might want to do is make his peace with Haftar and wait, as Haftar is old and he is still quite young by comparison. The future, or a good part of it, could yet be his. And then, perhaps, he could mete out his revenge upon those he would deem responsible for his father's overthrow.
Just my thoughts. I'd be interested in any comments you might have. These are certainly interesting times.
